What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loan entries in the dataset with 81 features (some of the features are LoanOriginalAmount, Term, BorrowerAPR, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, StatedMonthlyIncome, IncomeRange, MonthlyLoanPayment). Most of the variables are numeric in nature, and others are either of categorical or string data type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the borrower's Monthly Loan Payment for the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

With so many features to consider, I believe that the LoanOriginalAmount, Term, and StatedMonthlyIncome will have a strong effect on the Borrower's Monthly Loan Payment: The higher the LoanOriginalAmount, the higher the MonthlyLoanPayment; An increase in the Loan Term will reduce the MonthlyLoanPayment and also the higher the StatedMonthlyIncome the higher the MonthlyLoanPayment. I also suspect that other features like BorrowerAPR, EmploymentStatus, IncomeRange, and Investors, will have effects on the MonthlyLoanPayment, though not as much as the Term, LoanOriginalAmount and StatedMonthlyIncome.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Monthly Loan Payment.

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead

plt.show()

MonthlyLoanPayment has a long-tailed distribution and we find that a bulk of the entries are below $500. When plotted on a log-scale, the MonthlyLoanPayment distribution is skewed to the right.

#combine "Not employed", "Not sdisplayed" and "$0" Income ranges together

df_loan['IncomeRange'].replace(['Not employed', 'Not displayed'], '$0', inplace = True)
In [18]:
# create ordinal categories for income
ordinal_rating = ['$100,000+', '$75,000-99,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$1-24,999', '$0']
ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_rating)
df_loan['IncomeRange'] = df_loan['IncomeRange'].astype(ordered_var)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The MonthlyLoanPayment variable had a large range of values and thus produced a long-tailed distribution, so i looked at the data using a log transform. Under the log transformation, the data skewed to the right, with most of the values around and between $500.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

On further investigation into the predictor variables, the StatedMonthlyIncome was misleading when plotted on a standard scale, so a log transformation was used and it produced a unimodal distribution. A log transformation was also used to plot the Investors variable as the standard scale produced a long-tailed distribution. I decided to tidy the IncomeRange variable by combining 'Not employed', 'Not displayed' values to '$0' in the dataset.

From the above visualisations, it can be seen that the MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount are highly correlated with each other which is expected.

It was expected that the StatedMonthlyIncome would be highly correlated with both the MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount but Surprisingly, a weak correlation is observed between StatedMonthlyIncome and both the MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount.

Another point of attention is the negative correlation between the MonthlyLoanPayment and BorrowerAPR. Earlier assumptions quoted that a higher BorrowerAPR would witness a corresponding higher MonthlyLoanpayment.

Moving further, I will be looking at how the MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount correlate with the categorical variables.

In [50]:
loan_samp = df_loan.sample(n=2000, replace = False)


def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color=default_color);

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sns.PairGrid(data = loan_samp, y_vars = ['MonthlyLoanPayment', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], x_vars = cat_vars,
                height = 3, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid);
g.fig.suptitle("PAIRPLOT SHOWING RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN NUMERICAL VARIABLES", y=1.01);
plt.xticks(rotation=30);
plt.show();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

MonthlyLoanPayment had a high amount of correlation with the LoanOriginalAmount. I had expected to see a bit of correlation between the MonthlyLoanPayment and the BorrowerAPR, but surprisingly they were negatively correlated. Also, I had some assumptions that the MonthlyLoanPayment would be influenced by strongly by the StatedMonthlyIncome (i.e A higher Monthly Income would attract a higher Monthly Loan Payment - Positive correlation) but a weak correlation was seen.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I had expected a positive correlation between the LoanOriginalAmount and the BorrowerAPR but instead a negative correlation was observed. Also, there was a small interaction in the categorical Loan variables.

Conclusions¶

From the analysis performed above, It was seen that the LoanOriginalAmount has an effect on the MonthlyLoanPayment (positive correlation - an increase in LoanOriginalAmount saw an increase in the MonthlyLoanPayment). Also, further investigation revealed that the Term of the Loan affected that relationship (the longer the Term, the lower the MonthlyLoanPayment).
